  "summary": "Hercule Poirot explains to a companion that the complex case involving mysterious clocks was a plot orchestrated by Miss Marple. Using the unpublished manuscripts of the deceased author Gary Greggson, Miss Marple acted as a mastermind, manipulating local characters to follow the plots she discovered in his notebooks. Poirot reveals that the clocks' specific times—5:14:54, 5:07:07, and 5:05:05—formed the password (514547) to a safe hidden behind a replica of the Mona Lisa, which contained the Russian royal crown. Poirot provides contact information for Mr. Endebie, an international lawyer in Canada, to assist with further investigations.\n\nLater, Colin Lamb visits Miss Mina Pemukho at her home on Wilbraham Crescent. Colin reveals he has uncovered her role as the headquarters of a criminal plot, noting how she used braille to secure records and how information was transmitted via Lymes. Despite her blindness, Colin recognizes her intelligence and danger, disarming her when she attempts to use a knife against him. He informs her that specialized personnel will arrive in two hours and offers her a chance to leave. Colin expresses a desire for her to become his mother-in-law, though he admits he does not trust her. He subsequently announces his intention to return to marine biology in Australia.\n\nA letter from Richard Hakast to Poirot confirms that the body identified as Harry Castleton was actually Quentin Dugastlin. The letter notes that Valerie Brand (née Montreux) is the niece of the late Henry Montreux and that her sister, Miss Martinchel, was involved in the crime. Subsequent notes from Richard Huckleberry reveal that Mrs. Brand confessed, claiming her sister and husband orchestrated the scheme and that she was only informed at the last moment. Additionally, Miss Martin was identified as the woman who purchased the two clocks.",
